UNICEF in collaboration with State Universal Basic Education Board, (SUBEB), have distributed learning materials to 202,817 pupils in Adamawa state. Mr Ishaya Joel, UNICEF Education Consultants at the Flag-off event in Yola Tuesday said, 5,070 teachers also benefit from the intervention in 5 LGAs of the state. Joel stated that, over 5000 school bags would be distributed across Girei, Yola-South, Mubi-North, Fufore and Guyuk LGAs under the project tagged ‘UNICEF School Supply’. He said UNICEF since 2014 has  so far rehabilitated 369 class rooms for 123 primary schools in 15 councils  and supplied furniture to 2,434 schools. According to him the 3 Joint Education Need Assessment (JENA), conducted, enrollment and tracking of 194,883 pupils in the affected councils. Other interventions includes provision of 15,209 uniform set for girls, 841 school-in-a-box for teachers as well as 326 temporary learning space for displaced schools. He noted that, “UNICEF had engaged community through establishment of school based management committee (SBMC) in 337 schools and 2 IDP camps” Earlier Hajiya Fadimatu Alfa, Acting Executive Secretary ASUBEB in her remarks said is first of its kind that state received large consignment of instructional materials. Alfa further added that, 625 cartoons of school bags for 25,000 pupils and 5,050 will be given set of teaching materials. She explained each cartoon contains exercise books, biros pencils, slates, crayon colors, rulers, nylon bags, erasers sharpeners solid tape and scissors for the 202,874 pupils in the state. 